## 15. Interview One-Liners

### "Walk me through the design."
> "API Gateway placement, stack rules by user ID / IP / API key, Token Bucket algorithm, sharded Redis for state, Lua scripts for atomic updates, HTTP 429 + headers on reject."

### "Why Token Bucket?"
> "Handles bursts + sustained rate naturally, tiny memory (2 fields per user), and two intuitive knobs — bucket size and refill rate. Stripe uses it in production."

### "How do you fix the race condition?"
> "Lua scripts in Redis. Redis runs them atomically and single-threaded, so read-compute-write happens without interleaving."

### "How do you scale to 1M rps?"
> "Shard Redis by client ID via Redis Cluster. Ten shards × 100k ops/sec = 1M rps."

### "Fail open or fail closed?"
> "Fail closed for social media. Rate limiter failures usually coincide with traffic spikes, and failing open turns an outage into a cascade."

### "How do you stay under 10ms latency?"
> "Connection pooling (skips 20-50ms TCP handshake) and geo-distribution (regional Redis instead of cross-continent)."

### "How do you handle hot keys?"
> "Client-side throttling and batching for legitimate high-volume clients; automatic blocklists and upstream DDoS shield for abuse."

